<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-585-114  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 585 114.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 25 1990 v24 n26 p27(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM's storage strategy: playing to mixed reviews. ( System ManagedStorage)(includes related article on IBM's plans for developingSystem Managed Storage)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bochenski, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users and developers give a mixed review to IBM's System ManagedStorage (SMS) strategy.andP;  The goal of SMS is automation of thestorage management function.andP;  It puts logical data sets in thebest storage media, whether direct access storage devices (DASD),tape or main memory.andP;  In this manner, memory management functionscan be handled more efficiently and better utilization ofavailable storage capacity is possible.andP;  Bear Creek Corp (Bedford,OR) uses SMS to handle its 90Gbytes of stored data as it operatesa worldwide gift shipment business.andP;  The utilization of SMS, whichis only available for IBM systems such as ESA, MVS/XA and VM,requires the re-evaluation of an MIS operation's data setutilization.andP;  Considerable opportunities for third-partydevelopers to fill niches left by IBM are emerging.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development)Bear Creek Corp. (automation).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Direct Access Storage DevicesManagement of EDPThird-Party VendorsStorage AllocationNew Technique.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>